This paper is about neural machine translation (NMT) models, which are typically studied in the natural language processing (NLP) community. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper proposes a novel approach to address the challenge of translating into morphologically-rich languages, which involves modeling word formation through a hierarchical latent variable model. This approach involves both continuous and discrete features, which are learned from the translation data. Therefore, the paper is likely to be relevant to the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), and neural networks (cs.NE). Additionally, the paper involves generating words one character at a time, which is a task that can be relevant to computer vision (cs.CV) as well.
